to burn incense: Where so many sacrifices were offered, it was
essentially necessary to have some pleasing perfume to counteract the
disagreeable smells that must have arisen from the slaughter of so many
animals, the burning of so much flesh, the sprinkling of the blood. No
blood was ever sprinkled on this altar, except once a year, on the grand
day of expiation. It was called also the golden altar ([Num
4:11](../../../bib/kjv/num004.htm#011).md); and the incense was as
constantly burnt on it every day, as the morning and evening sacrifice
of a lamb was burnt on the brazen altar.

